    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_785997284" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/785997284" />
    <a title="Drew" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22104588-drew"><img alt="Drew" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1498412758p2/22104588.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/785997284?book_show_action=true">Dec 09, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Drew" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Drew" href="/user/show/22104588-drew">Drew</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22104588-drew?shelf=young-adult">young-adult</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22104588-drew?shelf=sci-fi">sci-fi</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer785997284" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17195479408731385835">Well, this was quite the unexpected surprise! <i>The Declaration</i> was such a nice, enjoyable, short read, compared to what I thought would be another shallow dystopian book.<br/><br/>The storyline was incredibly fascinating and just got more intriguing the more I read. It really was nothing like I expected. In another futuristic, messed-up world, drugs that stop all sicknesses and suppress old age have been created. But with nobody dying anymore, the Earth is slowly filling up, so a new rule is applied if you</span>
  <span id="freeText17195479408731385835" style="display:none">Well, this was quite the unexpected surprise! <i>The Declaration</i> was such a nice, enjoyable, short read, compared to what I thought would be another shallow dystopian book.<br /><br />The storyline was incredibly fascinating and just got more intriguing the more I read. It really was nothing like I expected. In another futuristic, messed-up world, drugs that stop all sicknesses and suppress old age have been created. But with nobody dying anymore, the Earth is slowly filling up, so a new rule is applied if you want to take the drugs (which everyone does): you have to sign the Declaration, promising you won't have any children.<br /><br />Anna is a teenaged "Surplus," and lives in Grange Hall, which is basically an institute for turning illegal children into slaves. In this place, all the kids are brainwashed into thinking they shouldn't have been born, are worthless, and owe "Mother Nature" their lives (who they are taught to regard as God).<blockquote>
  <i>"Surplus meant unnecessary. Not required."</i>
</blockquote>I was surprised to find the author's writing to be quite simple, which made the book seem to be aimed more at preteens than teenagers, but I would still label it "young adult" over "middle grade" because of some violence toward the end. And although the writing wasn't quite as intricate as I had expected it to be—and maybe I was over the reading age limit—I was still able to thoroughly enjoy it just fine.<br /><br />I didn't mind Anna as a character, though I wished she'd been a little more complex. I <i>did</i> find Peter to be slightly annoying, the way that he was always coming to Anna's rescue and making moony eyes at her one minute and calling her "stupid" the next.<br /><br />Other than that, I didn't really have any problems with this book. I do think Gemma Malley could've done a better job at writing the ending; I didn't like the way everything was tied up so perfectly. A nice little cliffhanger would've made me look forward to starting the next book even more (though I'm still quite excited to read the rest of the series).<b>
  <i>
    <blockquote>"The Authorities don't want people to Opt Out, they don't want any new children, because that might change the balance of power. They like things the way they are, and they're afraid of change, so they suppress it. They kill it off at the roots. You are the revolution, Anna."</blockquote>
  </i>
</b></span>
  <a data-text-id="17195479408731385835" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


