    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_198650917" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/198650917" />
    <a title="Mark" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2569035-mark"><img alt="Mark" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1455213348p2/2569035.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/198650917?book_show_action=true">Aug 15, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mark" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mark" href="/user/show/2569035-mark">Mark</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780747587743" href="/book/show/3217299-the-declaration">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2569035-mark?shelf=chronicles-series">chronicles-series</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2569035-mark?shelf=young-adult-fiction">young-adult-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer198650917" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer478655921305768297">Have just had a weekend of teen fiction though when I bought this book and &apos; I am number four&apos; a few months ago I did not realize they were written for the younger end of the market. This is a cleverly chilling concept of society in which a drug called &apos; Longevity&apos; has resulted in old age, or at least death, becoming something one opts into, bringing about the horrendous situation where children become as rare as hens&apos; teeth and can only be born if the parent is prepared to die for them; a life </span>
  <span id="freeText478655921305768297" style="display:none">Have just had a weekend of teen fiction though when I bought this book and ' I am number four' a few months ago I did not realize they were written for the younger end of the market. This is a cleverly chilling concept of society in which a drug called ' Longevity' has resulted in old age, or at least death, becoming something one opts into, bringing about the horrendous situation where children become as rare as hens' teeth and can only be born if the parent is prepared to die for them; a life for a life. One in, one out. Otherwise they become ' surplus' illegals who ought not to be around and therefore live lives of degradation and oppression unallowed to enjoy even the basic elements of normal lfe. Malley suggests implications of this awful nightmare society but leaves the ideas floating in the ether. Maybe this is her intention, to challenge us to reflect on issues as diverse as ecology and sustainability, the inevitability of ageing and the fear of death and the need to nurture the young, the centrality of loving relationships for our proper development and the concept that nobody is surplus no matter how many others may say this, once they feel loved. As a result of this 'love as the answer to all things' central premise there is what seems to me to be the shoehorning of a burgeoning innocent love affair between the two main characters into the centre of the story. I can fully understand why Malley did this; the love of parents may or may not exist in this society but the love of individuals for each other is what gives the hope. However I wonder whether the romance which is rather awkwardly constructed takes away from and dilutes the central challenges of what could be a very thought provoking book</span>
  <a data-text-id="478655921305768297" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


